It is easy to see that the labeling $f$ above is super.\\ \
\\
The edge-weight of the edge $u_iv_j, \ \ 1\leq i\leq n,\ \ 1\leq j\leq m$ is given as:
\begin{eqnarray*}

  wt_f(u_iv_j) &=& f(u_i)+f(u_iv_j)+f(v_j)\\
   &=& \left\{\begin{array}{c}{\hspace{-0.5cm}}n(1+j)+2m-1+j+1,\ \ \ 1\leq i\leq n,\ \ \ 1\leq j\leq m-n,\\n(2+j)+m-i+2j+1,\ \ \ 1\leq i\leq n,\ \ \ m-n+1\leq j\leq m\end{array}\right.
\end{eqnarray*}


The weights of all the edges in $K_{n,m}$ are different under the labeling $f$ which means that the labeling $f$ is EAT.\\ \ \\
We also have to check that the vertex-weights are different. \\
For vertex $u_i,\ \ \ 1\leq i\leq n$, we get:
\begin{eqnarray*}

  wt_f(u_i) &=& f(u_i)+\sum^m_{j=1}f(u_iv_j) \\
   &=&  n+m-2i+1+\sum_{j=1}^mm+nj+i\\
   &=& i(m-2)+\frac{m}{2}((1+m)(n+2))+n+1 \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (2.3)
\end{eqnarray*}



Also, for vertex $v_j, \ \ \ 1\leq j\leq m$, we get
\begin{eqnarray*}

  wt_f(v_j) &=& f(v_j)+\sum^n_{i=1}f(u_iv_j),\ \ \ \ 1\leq j\leq m \\
   &=& \left\{\begin{array}{c}{\hspace{-0.5cm}}j(1+n^2)+\frac{n}{2}(1+n+2m),\ \ \ 1\leq j\leq m-n,\\j(2+n^2)+\frac{n}{2}(3+n+2m)-m,\ \ \ m-n+1\leq j\leq m\end{array}\right.  \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (2.4)
\end{eqnarray*}


From equation (2.3), we have that $wt_f(u_i)<wt_f(u_{i+1}),\ \ \ 1\leq i\leq n-1$, whenever $f(u_i)<f(u_{i+1})$. Also, from equation (2.4), we have that $wt_f(v_j)<wt_f(v_{j+1}), \ \ \ 1\leq j\leq m-1$, whenever $f(v_j)<f(v_{j+1})$. Therefore, $K_{n,m}$ is a weak ordered graph.
Hence, $K_{n,m}$ is a TAT graph since the labeling $f$ is both EAT and VAT.
\end{proof}


